<DOC><DOCNO> AP900420-0049 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-90 0546EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Soldiers     04-20 0216</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Israel-Soldiers,0222</SECOND><HEAD>Three Soldiers Sentenced In Bread Case</HEAD><DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A religious soldier has been jailed forthreatening to shoot two fellow soldiers who ate bread duringPassover and made scathing remarks about a leading rabbi, the armysaid today.   The devout soldier was sentenced to 28 days in the stockade forhis threat, and the other two were given 14 days each for mockingthe religious beliefs of a fellow soldier, an army spokesman said.   The army bars the eating of bread on bases during Passover,which commemorates the flight of the Jews from slavery in Egypt.Jews eat unleavened matzah during the eight-day holiday tosymbolize the hasty escape in which the Jews did not have time tomake real bread.   The confrontation came at a base in central Israel where thethree soldiers were talking politics, Israeli newspapers and radioreported.   When the two secular soldiers criticized Rabbi Eliezer Schachand began eating bread, the religious soldier cocked his gun andthreatened to shoot them, according to the reports. The two secularsoldiers calmed him down, the reports said.   Schach, 96, is the spiritual leader of two ultra-Orthodoxpolitical parties. He has been at the center of a controversy overwhether small religious parties have too much power in Israelipolitics.</TEXT></DOC>